,"Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England":"Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England"},"nl":{"1378–":"1378–Overleden","1378–Female":"1378–Overleden","1379–1431":"1379–1431","1406–1496":"1406–1496","1411–Female":"1411–Overleden","1414–Male":"1414–Overleden","1418–Female":"1418–Overleden","1420–1494":"1420–1494","–1460":"–1460","–Male":"Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","2 May 1405":"2 mei 1405","1414":"1414","1379":"1379","1378":"1378","1411":"1411","1420":"1420","1431":"1431","1496":"1496","1494":"1494","1460":"1460","1418":"1418","1406":"1406","Saredon, Staffordshire, England":"Saredon, Staffordshire, England","Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Stanton, Oxfordshire, England":"Stanton St John, Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England":"Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England"},"en":{"1378–":"1378–Deceased","1378–Female":"1378–Deceased","1379–1431":"1379–1431","1406–1496":"1406–1496","1411–Female":"1411–Deceased","1414–Male":"1414–Deceased","1418–Female":"1418–Deceased","1420–1494":"1420–1494","–1460":"–1460","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","2 May 1405":"2 May 1405","1414":"1414","1379":"1379","1378":"1378","1411":"1411","1420":"1420","1431":"1431","1496":"1496","1494":"1494","1460":"1460","1418":"1418","1406":"1406","Saredon, Staffordshire, England":"Saredon, Staffordshire, England","Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Stanton, Oxfordshire, England":"Stanton St John, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England":"Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lutley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: variant of   Littley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Littley","meanings":["1  English: nickname from Middle English  <i>litel</i> ‘little’ (Old English  <i>lȳtel</i>) +  <i>eye</i> ‘eye’ (Old English  <i>ēage</i>).  Compare  Mussey  . Some post-medieval bearers given here may alternatively belong to (2) or (3).","2  English: formally it could be a locative name derived from Old English  <i>lȳtel</i> ‘little’ +  <i>ēg</i> ‘island’, but no such place-name is known. It cannot be decided whether the surname of this origin has survived or whether some bearers under (1) belong here.","3  English: locative name from Likeley Wood in Wickham Bishops (Essex), which is recorded as  <i>Litlehey</i> in 1340, or from any of the numerous other places with names deriving from Old English  <i>lȳtel</i> +  <i>gehæg</i> ‘little enclosure’, such as Littley Green in Great Waltham, Littley Wood in Wethersfield, and Littleys in Ashdon (all Essex), Litley in Cheadle and Little Hay in Shenstone (both Staffs)."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Lutley was born in 1378 as the daughter of Samuel Francis and Mary. She married Sir Richard Harcourt on 2 May 1405, in Stanton St John, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 2 daughters."},"et":{"1378–":"1378–Surnud","1378–Female":"1378–Surnud","1379–1431":"1379–1431","1406–1496":"1406–1496","1411–Female":"1411–Surnud","1414–Male":"1414–Surnud","1418–Female":"1418–Surnud","1420–1494":"1420–1494","–1460":"–1460","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","2 May 1405":"2. mai 1405","1414":"1414","1379":"1379","1378":"1378","1411":"1411","1420":"1420","1431":"1431","1496":"1496","1494":"1494","1460":"1460","1418":"1418","1406":"1406","Saredon, Staffordshire, England":"Saredon, Staffordshire, England","Oxfordshire,